{"id":"1604.03175","submitter":"Stratis Ioannidis","authors":"Stratis Ioannidis, Edmund Yeh","title":"Adaptive Caching Networks with Optimality Guarantees","comments":"This is the extended version of: \"Adaptive Caching Networks with\n  Optimality Guarantees\", Stratis Ioannidis and Edmund Yeh, SIGMETRICS 2016","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.NI","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We study the problem of optimal content placement over a network of caches, a\nproblem naturally arising in several networking applications, including ICNs,\nCDNs, and P2P systems. Given a demand of content request rates and paths\nfollowed, we wish to determine the content placement that maximizes the\nexpected caching gain, i.e., the reduction of routing costs due to intermediate\ncaching. The offline version of this problem is NP-hard and, in general, the\ndemand and topology may be a priori unknown. Hence, a distributed, adaptive,\nconstant approximation content placement algorithm is desired. We show that\npath replication, a simple algorithm frequently encountered in literature, can\nbe arbitrarily suboptimal when combined with traditional eviction policies,\nlike LRU, LFU, or FIFO. We propose a distributed, adaptive algorithm that\nperforms stochastic gradient ascent on a concave relaxation of the expected\ncaching gain, and constructs a probabilistic content placement within 1-1/e\nfactor from the optimal, in expectation. Motivated by our analysis, we also\npropose a novel greedy eviction policy to be used with path replication, and\nshow through numerical evaluations that both algorithms significantly\noutperform path replication with traditional eviction policies over a broad\narray of network topologies.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 11 Apr 2016 23:25:18 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-04-13"}
